<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "What Is a Differential Equation?"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-connection-to-alg-calc.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-de-defn.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-variables.ptx
		c0-whats-a-de/sec-terms-coeffs.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ 01 intro-topics folder
	Companion worksheet for c1 classification: ws-classification.ptx

	Worksheet conventions (see CLAUDE.md section 4):
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    selected by <source><version include="notes stu|key"/> in the
	    publication files. Both versions mirror each other in structure.
	  * Reading-check blanks: paired <p component="stu"> (with <fillin/>)
	    and <p component="key"> (answers as underlined bold math). The
	    answer NEVER lives inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    (statement only, generous write-in space) and
	    <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * <page> delimits vertical space for letter-size printing, NOT topics.
	    Headings are <p><term>...</term></p>, never page titles.
	  * Display math uses <md>; <me>/<men> are deprecated.
	  * <example> renders its solution in BOTH builds; reserve it for
	    read-along illustrations with nothing hidden.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-what-is-a-de" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>What Is a Differential Equation?</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Identify</term> whether an equation is a differential equation, and name its dependent and independent variables.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Connect</term> solving a differential equation to solving equations in algebra and to antidifferentiation.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Label</term> the terms, free term, and coefficients of a differential equation.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : What is a DE? Variables, terms, coefficients                -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>What is a differential equation?</term></p>

		<p>
			In algebra you solved equations like <m>y - 3t = 5</m> for a
			<em>number</em> <m>y</m>. A differential equation asks a harder question:
			it hands you information about a function <em>and its derivatives</em> and
			asks you to find the whole <em>function</em>. For instance, isolating the
			derivative in <m>y' - 3t = 5</m> gives <m>y' = 5 + 3t</m>, and the job is
			to find a function whose derivative is <m>5 + 3t</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check: one paragraph of blanks, then ONE remark. -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A differential equation is an equation that involves one or more
						<fillin characters="12"/> of an unknown function.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A differential equation is an equation that involves one or more
						<m>\underline{\textbf{derivatives}}</m> of an unknown function.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						For an equation to be a differential equation it must contain both a
						derivative and an <fillin characters="12"/> sign.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						For an equation to be a differential equation it must contain both a
						derivative and an <m>\underline{\textbf{equals}}</m> sign.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						If the unknown function depends on a single variable the equation is
						an <fillin characters="10"/> differential equation; if it
						depends on more than one variable it is a <fillin characters="9"/>
						differential equation. In this course, when we say <q>differential 
						equation</q> we mean  <fillin characters="10"/> differential equation.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						If the unknown function depends on a single variable the equation is
						an <m>\underline{\textbf{ordinary}}</m> differential equation; if it
						depends on more than one variable it is a 
						<m>\underline{\textbf{partial}}</m> differential equation. In this 
						course, when we say <q>differential equation</q> we mean 
						<m>\underline{\textbf{ordinary}}</m> differential equation.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-diff-eq">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p><m>y''' - 4y' - 3</m> is a differential equation.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					False. It has derivatives of the dependent variable <m>y</m>, but it 
					has no equals sign.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-antideriv" component="stu" workspace="1.1in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the differential equation <m>y' = 5 + 3t</m> by finding a
					function <m>y</m> whose derivative is <m>5 + 3t</m>. Why is there more
					than one answer?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-antideriv" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the differential equation <m>y' = 5 + 3t</m> by finding a
					function <m>y</m> whose derivative is <m>5 + 3t</m>. Why is there more
					than one answer?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Antidifferentiate both sides: <m>y = 5t + \frac{3}{2}t^2 + C</m>. Every choice of
					the constant <m>C</m> gives a function whose derivative is
					<m>5 + 3t</m>, so a first-order differential equation has a whole
					<em>family</em> of solutions rather than a single one. This is the
					recurring theme of the course: solving a differential equation means
					recovering a function, and the arbitrary constant is the fingerprint of
					the integration we did to get there.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<page>
		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-variables" component="stu" workspace="2.0in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each differential equation, name the dependent variable (the
					unknown function we solve for) and the independent variable (the one it
					is differentiated with respect to):
					<md>
						\frac{dW}{dz} + \frac{W}{z} = 9z^2, \qquad
						g'' + s^3 g = 0, \qquad
						R''' = 6R.
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ic-ex-variables" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each differential equation, name the dependent variable (the
					unknown function we solve for) and the independent variable (the one it
					is differentiated with respect to):
					<md>
						\frac{dW}{dz} + \frac{W}{z} = 9z^2, \qquad
						g'' + s^3 g = 0, \qquad
						R''' = 6R.
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The derivative tells you which variable is which&#8212;the dependent
					variable is the one being differentiated.
					<ul marker="square">
						<li><p><m>dW/dz</m> means <m>W</m> changes as <m>z</m> changes: dependent <m>W</m>, independent <m>z</m>.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>g''</m> is a derivative of <m>g</m> with respect to <m>s</m>: dependent <m>g</m>, independent <m>s</m>.</p></li>
						<li><p><m>R'''</m> shows <m>R</m> is the dependent variable; no independent variable is named, so you may call it whatever you like (say <m>t</m>).</p></li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<term>Vocabulary for the parts of an equation.</term> Before we can
			classify equations we need names for their pieces. Fill in the blanks.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A <term>term</term> is any piece of a differential equation separated
						from the others by <fillin characters="18"/> signs.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A <term>term</term> is any piece of a differential equation separated
						from the others by <m>\underline{\textbf{plus or minus}}</m> signs.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A <term>free term</term> is a term that does <em>not</em> involve the
						<fillin characters="11"/> variable or its derivatives. Every equation
						has one, even a hidden <fillin characters="11"/>: for example
						<m>w' = 4w</m> is really <m>w' - 4w = 0</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A <term>free term</term> is a term that does <em>not</em> involve the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{dependent}}</m> variable or its derivatives. Every 
						equation has one, even a hidden <m>\underline{\textbf{free term}}</m>: for example
						<m>w' = 4w</m> is really <m>w' - 4w = 0</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						A <term>coefficient</term> is a constant or a function of the
						<fillin characters="13"/> variable that multiplies the dependent
						variable or one of its derivatives.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						A <term>coefficient</term> is a constant or a function of the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{independent}}</m> variable that multiplies the dependent
						variable or one of its derivatives.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-tf-ex-coeffs">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>A coefficient may never contain the dependent variable.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. A coefficient may be a constant or a function of the independent
					variable, but it may not contain the dependent variable or any of its
					derivatives.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<title>Terms, free term, and coefficients</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The dependent variable below is <m>u</m>:
					<md>
						\frac{5}{t}\,u^{(4)} + 2.7\,u'' + t^3 u' + u = \tfrac14 e^{2t}.
					</md>
					(a) List the five terms. (b) Which is the free term? (c) Give the
					coefficient of <m>u^{(4)}</m>, of <m>u''</m>, of <m>u'</m>, and of
					<m>u</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise component="key">
			<title>Terms, free term, and coefficients</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The dependent variable below is <m>u</m>:
					<md>
						\frac{5}{t}\,u^{(4)} + 2.7\,u'' + t^3 u' + u = \tfrac14 e^{2t}.
					</md>
					(a) List the five terms. (b) Which is the free term? (c) Give the
					coefficient of <m>u^{(4)}</m>, of <m>u''</m>, of <m>u'</m>, and of
					<m>u</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) The terms are <m>\frac{5}{t}u^{(4)}</m>, <m>2.7\,u''</m>,
					<m>t^3 u'</m>, <m>u</m>, and <m>\frac14 e^{2t}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) The free term is <m>\frac14 e^{2t}</m>: it contains the independent
					variable <m>t</m> but none of <m>u</m> or its derivatives. (Notice a
					free term need not be constant&#8212;this is why <q>constant term</q> is
					a misleading name.)
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Reading off the multipliers of the dependent variable and its
					derivatives: coefficient of <m>u^{(4)}</m> is <m>\frac{5}{t}</m>, of
					<m>u''</m> is <m>2.7</m>, of <m>u'</m> is <m>t^3</m>, and of <m>u</m> is
					<m>1</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Naming the parts of a differential equation is the first step toward
				<em>classifying</em> it. In the next worksheet we attach two labels to
				every equation&#8212;its <em>order</em> and whether it is
				<em>linear</em>&#8212;because together they decide which solution
				technique to reach for.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
